Preheat your #oven{} to 200°C. Pop the @mild curry powder{1%tsp} in a #bowl{} and add a third of the @Greek style natural yoghurt{75%g}. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{} and mix together. Add the @diced British chicken thigh{210%g} and stir to coat in the spiced yoghurt. Line a #baking tray{} with @foil{} and pop the chicken on the tray in a single layer. Set aside for a couple of mins.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands after handling raw meat.

Halve, peel and thinly slice the @onion{1}(halved and sliced thinly). Trim the @green beans{80%g}(trimmed and cut into thirds) and cut into three pieces. Peel and grate the @garlic{2%cloves}(peeled and grated) (or use a #garlic press{}).

Bake the chicken on the top shelf of your oven until slightly golden and cooked through, ~{12-15%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: The chicken is cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

Heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a #frying pan{} on medium high heat. Once hot, add the onion, reduce the heat to medium and fry until it's evenly golden and starting to soften, ~{5-6%minutes}. Add the green beans and stir fry with the onion until starting to char, ~{2-3%minutes}. Add the @mustard seeds{1%tsp}, garlic and @korma curry paste{50%g}, stir and cook for ~{1%minute}, then add the @tomato passata{1%jar}, @water{100%ml} and @chicken stock powder{1%tsp}.

Season the sauce with @salt{}, @pepper{} and a pinch of @sugar{}. Bring to the boil, then reduce the heat to medium and simmer until reduced by a third, ~{4-5%minutes}. Meanwhile, cook the @steamed basmati rice{1%pot} according to pack instructions. Once the chicken is cooked, add it to the sauce with any juices and stir to combine. Remove from the heat and stir in the remaining greek yoghurt.

> TIP: Don't boil the yoghurt or it might split.

Taste the sauce and add salt and pepper if you feel it needs it, add a splash of @water{} too if you feel it needs loosening up. Serve the rice in #bowls{} topped with the curry. Enjoy!